<br>
As a Skald, you drop quite fast. AoF+AP will let you survive longer especially when hit by an assist train, giving more chances for your healer to help you, more chances for AF/Ablative/mending/lifedrain reactives to proc. Frontloaded damage on a Skald will kill you almost instantly, and usually in this kind of situation IP lags off and you die. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c2a2><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sligg0rz>Sligg0rz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Participant</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#ff0000>(11/12/03 1:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=704.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: One more thing...</span><hr size=1> Or...<br>
<br>
You could spend less time arguing and making polls and go farm RPs to get **all of the above**.<br>
<br>
Also, no amount of passives can ever justify not getting IP or AP2/AoF. Active RAs are much much more important. Consider just Mastery of Pain.<br>
<br>
Mastery of Pain = +5% chance to critical hit. The cap on critical hits is 50% of total damage. The average critical hit is 25% (equal chance to have a 1% crit as a 50% crit). Therefore for each level of Mastery of Pain your total damage increases by 1.25% (25% average crit multiplied by 5% additional chance to crit). Passives are nice if you have extra Realm ability points to spare, but for 1.25% additional damage I cannot see it being worth sacrificing any good actives.<br>
<br>
Lets say that IP is up every third fight (which is probably average for me , but extremely conservative for most players). Let us also assume that you have 2100 hps with Aug con 3. Now, lets try and quantify IP and spread out the value of that full insta heal over 3 battles. Simply put, though there are numerous variables preventing this from being anything more than mere conjecture, IP is almost like a permanent 700 hit point buff. Yes, sometimes it doesn't fire. Yes, you have to take action to give yourself these extra hps. Yes, there are numerous circumstances that seperate this from a passive ability. The fact remains that all things being equal, you get an average of 700 extra hps per battle. You cannot give yourself 700 extra hps with aug con 5, toughness 5.<br>
<br>
Now, Avoid Pain and Armor of Faith. AP2 is an extra 20% absorption. Others have done the math on this one, but Armor of Faith works out to around 5% additional absorb. So AP2 + AoF 2 = roughly 30% additional absorb. This ability is up for me roughly 2 out of 3 fights if slightly less. For most players this ability is going to be up in almost every group battle. Lets use the 2/3 number, however. This is going to be even less concrete than what we can do with IP. Lets hypothetically say that one takes an average of 1400 points of damage in a group fight. This takes group wipes into account as well as easily won fights and hard fought battles requiring a lot of healing. Again, this is far from concrete, but it will serve well enough as an illustration. Lets say that you fire up AP2/AoF2 at the beginning of each of those fights (also a stretch I realize, but I am starting to fire it up before I even get hit these days). Using the above numbers, in 3 fights you would take a total of 4200 damage. Activating AP2+ AoF2 would save you an average of 420 damage per activation. which in the above 3 fights is a total of 840 damage. <br>
<br>
Again, even in these hypothetical situations with fictional data we can see that actives, even if we take an extremely conservative stance, play a bigger role in deciding battles than passives. I do understand that these are merely hypothetical sitautions and cannot be taken as raw data. The truth is that we can never measure the effect of active realm abilities because this whole discussion is very inconsistent and subjective, so this is the best way I could find to try and illustrate it.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#efe0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=baedemaentel>Baedemaentel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Participant</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/5/04 7:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=704.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: One more thing...</span><hr size=1> I think it's also a question of the personal fighring style and the way you die most often.<br>
<br>
IP and AP only help you if it gives you enough time to kill your opponent. It doesn't help you if you die anyway.<br>
<br>
I think IP helps you if you die a lot against 1 or 2 opponents and if all you needed is just this extra boos t of HPs.<br>
If you solo a lot (or play in small groups of 2 or 3), IP is really important because you don't have healers with you and IP simply can win the battle for you.<br>
<br>
If you group a lot, you either die because you take damage  quicker than your healers can heal it or because your group is loosing anyway. IP is most probably not going to help you in this situation.<br>
But AP/ AoF is. It gives the healers the extra time to heal you. It gives you the extra seconds to mezz one enemy caster and attack the second.<br>
<br>
I'll take AP because I run in groups more often than solo and I win a lot of solo (or 2vs2 fights) without IP.  <br>
I am a coward... When my opponent fires IP, I snare them and try to escape.<br>
<br>
